# AgentPrime - AI Coding Assistant IDE - Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
AgentPrime is a local-first AI coding workspace built with Electron, featuring:
- Multiple AI providers (Anthropic Claude, OpenAI GPT, Ollama, OpenRouter)
- Dual Model System with fast/deep/auto routing
- Template system for project generation (11 starter templates)
- Agent loop with tool-calling for autonomous coding tasks
- Python backend with FastAPI ("The Brain") for memory/orchestration
- Ghost text / inline completions via CompletionService
- Mirror Intelligence System for pattern learning
- Modular architecture with typed IPC communication

## Code Style & Conventions

### JavaScript/TypeScript
- Use ES6+ features, async/await over Promises
- Prefer arrow functions for concise expressions
- Use template literals over string concatenation
- Follow camelCase for variables/functions, PascalCase for classes/components
- Use meaningful variable names, avoid abbreviations
- Add JSDoc comments for public APIs and complex functions

### React Components
- Use functional components with hooks over class components
- Prefer custom hooks for reusable logic
- Use meaningful component and prop names
- Keep components small and focused (single responsibility)
- Use TypeScript interfaces for props and state

### Python Backend
- Follow PEP 8 style guidelines
- Use type hints for function parameters and return values
- Prefer f-strings over .format() or % formatting
- Use meaningful variable names, avoid single letters except for loops
- Add docstrings for all public functions and classes

### Error Handling
- Always handle errors gracefully with try/catch blocks
- Provide meaningful error messages
- Log errors appropriately (console.error for dev, proper logging for prod)
- Never expose sensitive information in error messages

## Architecture Patterns

### IPC Communication
- Use Electron's IPC for main ↔ renderer communication
- Define clear IPC channel names (e.g., 'fs:readFile', 'ai:chat')
- Validate all IPC message data before processing
- Handle IPC errors gracefully

### AI Provider Integration
- Implement consistent interface across all providers
- Handle API rate limits and errors appropriately
- Cache responses when appropriate
- Implement streaming support for real-time responses

### Template System
- Templates should be self-contained with package.json
- Include README.md with setup and usage instructions
- Use consistent naming and structure
- Test templates before adding to registry

## Security Considerations

### Electron Security
- Enable contextIsolation and nodeIntegration: false
- Use preload scripts for secure IPC communication
- Implement Content Security Policy (CSP) headers
- Validate all user inputs, especially file paths and URLs

### API Keys & Secrets
- Never commit API keys or secrets to version control
- Use environment variables for configuration
- Implement proper key validation and rotation
- Log API usage without exposing sensitive data

## Testing Requirements

### Unit Tests
- Write tests for all utility functions
- Test error conditions and edge cases
- Use descriptive test names (e.g., "should handle invalid file path")
- Aim for 80%+ code coverage

### Integration Tests
- Test IPC communication between main and renderer
- Test AI provider integrations with mock responses
- Test template generation and validation
- Use Playwright for end-to-end testing

### Performance Testing
- Monitor memory usage in Electron apps
- Test with large files and projects
- Profile AI API response times
- Optimize bundle sizes and load times

## Development Workflow

### New Features
1. Create feature branch from main
2. Write tests first (TDD approach)
3. Implement feature with clean, documented code
4. Test thoroughly across all supported platforms
5. Update documentation if needed
6. Create pull request with detailed description

### Bug Fixes
1. Reproduce the issue with clear steps
2. Write test case that reproduces the bug
3. Fix the issue with minimal changes
4. Ensure all existing tests still pass
5. Test fix across different environments

### Code Reviews
- Review for security vulnerabilities
- Check code style and conventions
- Verify tests are included and pass
- Ensure documentation is updated
- Test the changes manually if possible

## File Organization

### Main Application (src/)
- `main/` - Electron main process code
  - `ai-providers/` - AI provider implementations (Ollama, Anthropic, OpenAI, OpenRouter)
  - `core/` - Core business logic (state, telemetry, backend manager, budget, transactions)
  - `ipc-handlers/` - IPC communication handlers (files, git, templates, agent, search, etc.)
  - `mirror/` - Mirror Intelligence System (pattern memory, extraction, feedback loops)
  - `agent/` - Agent subsystem (validators, self-critique, tool verification, backup)
  - `agent-loop.ts` - Main tool-calling agent loop
  - `security/` - Secure key storage, IPC validation, workspace protection
  - `tools/` - Utility tools and helpers
  - `modules/` - ActivatePrime and other opt-in modules
- `renderer/` - React UI (components, hooks, agent client, services)
  - `components/` - App, AIChat, MonacoEditor, FileTree, SettingsPanel, etc.
  - `agent/` - Client-side agent loop, prompt builder, context manager
  - `services/` - CompletionService (ghost text)
- `cli/` - Commander-based CLI (agent, doctor, onboard, status)
- `types/` - Shared TypeScript type definitions

### Templates (templates/)
- Each template in its own directory
- Include package.json, README.md, and template.json
- Follow consistent structure and naming

### Backend (backend/)
- `app/` - FastAPI application ("The Brain")
  - `main.py` - App entry point with routers for files, chat, terminal, brain, team patterns
  - `core/` - Memory, orchestrator, analyzer
- `run.py` - Dev launcher
- `requirements.txt` - Python dependencies

## Build & Deployment

### Development
- Use `npm run dev` for main app development (concurrent webpack watch)
- Use `npm run quick-start` or `npm run start:dev` for build-then-run
- Backend starts automatically via backend-manager when configured
- Test on Windows, macOS, and Linux when possible

### Production Builds
- Use Electron Builder for desktop app packaging
- Include all necessary dependencies
- Test installers on clean systems
- Verify all features work in packaged app

### Release Process
1. Update version numbers in package.json files
2. Update changelog and release notes
3. Create GitHub release with installers
4. Update documentation if needed
5. Announce release to community

## Documentation

### Code Documentation
- Add JSDoc comments for all public APIs
- Document complex algorithms and business logic
- Include usage examples in comments
- Keep README files up to date

### User Documentation
- Maintain comprehensive README.md
- Include setup and installation instructions
- Document all features and keyboard shortcuts
- Provide troubleshooting guides

### API Documentation
- Document all IPC channels and message formats
- Document AI provider interfaces
- Include examples for custom integrations
- Keep API documentation synchronized with code

## Performance Optimization

### Electron Apps
- Minimize bundle sizes with code splitting
- Use virtual scrolling for large file trees
- Implement lazy loading for heavy components
- Monitor and optimize memory usage

### AI Integration
- Implement intelligent caching strategies
- Stream responses for better UX
- Handle API rate limits gracefully
- Optimize token usage and costs

### File Operations
- Use streaming for large file reads/writes
- Implement progress indicators for long operations
- Handle file locks and permissions properly
- Provide clear feedback for file operations

## Accessibility & UX

### Keyboard Navigation
- Support standard keyboard shortcuts
- Provide keyboard navigation for all UI elements
- Include screen reader support
- Test with keyboard-only navigation

### Visual Design
- Maintain consistent dark theme
- Use clear, readable fonts and colors
- Provide appropriate contrast ratios
- Include loading states and progress indicators

### Error Handling UX
- Provide clear, actionable error messages
- Include recovery options when possible
- Log errors for debugging while protecting user privacy
- Test error scenarios thoroughly

## Continuous Integration

